<p>We study a spatial version of the compartmental model depicted in 
 <xref rid="ppat.1004810.g001" ref-type="fig">Fig 1</xref>. This allows us to make predictions on the epidemiological and evolutionary consequences of spatial structure. First, 
 <xref rid="ppat.1004810.g002" ref-type="fig">Fig 2A</xref> shows that lower levels of mixing slow down the spread of the infection because in a spatially structured environment, pathogens experience a lower density of susceptible hosts. Second, the change in frequency of a virulent mutant strain is (see Supporting Information Theory in 
